    "reasoning": "The requirement is to implement a serial receiver FSM that detects valid bytes based on a specific protocol: 1 start bit (0), 8 data bits (LSB first), and 1 stop bit (1). If a stop bit is invalid, the FSM must wait for a valid stop bit (1) before looking for a new start bit. \n\nReasoning Steps:\n1. Define States: \n   - IDLE: Waiting for the start bit (0).\n   - START_BIT: Start bit detected, moving to receive data bits.\n   - DATA: Counting 8 bits of data.\n   - STOP_BIT: Checking the stop bit.\n   - WAIT_FOR_STOP: If the stop bit was incorrect (0), stay in this state until the line returns to 1.\n2. Data Collection: Use a register to shift in the 8 bits of data. Since the protocol is LSB first, we shift in data bits using `data_reg <= {in, data_reg[7:1]}` or similar.\n3. Transition Logic:\n   - From IDLE: If `in == 0`, move to START_BIT.\n   - From START_BIT: Move to DATA state with a bit counter initialized to 0.\n   - From DATA: Increment counter. When counter reaches 7, move to STOP_BIT.\n   - From STOP_BIT: If `in == 1`, output `done = 1` and return to IDLE. If `in == 0`, move to WAIT_FOR_STOP.\n   - From WAIT_FOR_STOP: If `in == 1`, return to IDLE. If `in == 0`, stay in WAIT_FOR_STOP.\n4. Output: `done` should be asserted for one cycle when a valid byte (including stop bit) is received.\n\nAdvice to avoid syntax errors:\n- Ensure all ports are declared as `logic` as requested.\n- Use `always @(posedge clk)` for sequential logic and `always @(*)` for combinational logic.\n- Use `localparam` for state definitions.\n- Use non-blocking assignments `<= ` for sequential logic and blocking assignments `= ` for combinational logic.",
    "module": "module TopModule(\n    input  logic clk,\n    input  logic reset,\n    input  logic in,\n    output logic done\n);\n\n    // State definitions\n    localparam STATE_IDLE         = 3'd0;\n    localparam STATE_START_BIT    = 3'd1;\n    localparam STATE_DATA         = 3'd2;\n    localparam STATE_STOP_BIT     = 3'd3;\n    localparam STATE_WAIT_FOR_STOP = 3'd4;\n\n    // State register\n    logic [2:0] state;\n    logic [2:0] state_next;\n\n    // Data and counter registers\n    logic [7:0] data_reg;\n    logic [3:0] bit_cnt;\n\n    // Sequential logic\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (reset) begin\n            state <= STATE_IDLE;\n            data_reg <= 8'b0;\n            bit_cnt <= 4'b0;\n        end else begin\n            state <= state_next;\n            \n            // Logic for data collection and bit counting\n            if (state == STATE_DATA) begin\n                data_reg <= {in, data_reg[7:1]}; // LSB first\n                bit_cnt <= bit_cnt + 1'b1;\n            end else if (state == STATE_START_BIT) begin\n                bit_cnt <= 0;\n            end else if (state == STATE_IDLE) begin\n                bit_cnt <= 0;\n            end else begin\n                bit_cnt <= 0;\n            end\n        end\n    end\n\n    // Next state combinational logic\n    always @(*) begin\n        state_next = state;\n        case (state) \n            STATE_IDLE: begin\n                if (in == 1'b0) \n                    state_next = STATE_START_BIT;\n                else\n                    state_next = STATE_IDLE;\n            end\n            STATE_START_BIT: begin\n                // After start bit is detected, we expect 8 data bits\n                state_next = STATE_DATA;\n            end\n            STATE_DATA: begin\n                if (bit_cnt == 4'd7) \n                    state_next = STATE_STOP_BIT;\n                else\n                    state_next = STATE_DATA;\n            end\n            STATE_STOP_BIT: begin\n                if (in == 1'b1) \n                    state_next = STATE_IDLE;\n                else\n                    state_next = STATE_WAIT_FOR_STOP;\n            end\n            STATE_WAIT_FOR_STOP: begin\n                // Wait until the line returns to 1 (idle/stop state)\n                if (in == 1'b1) \n                    state_next = STATE_IDLE;\n                else\n                    state_next = STATE_WAIT_FOR_STOP;\n            end\n            default: state_next = STATE_IDLE;\n        endcase\n    end\n\n    // Output logic\n    // done is high for one cycle when a valid stop bit is detected\n    always @(*) begin\n        if (state == STATE_STOP_BIT && in == 1'b1) \n            done = 1'b1;\n        else\n            done = 1'b0;\n    end\n\nendmodule"
}
